2026-04-16 12:18:19 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module inverted‑cables indicator LED branch (series LED and resistor wiring)', 'Load module series protection diode'] hypothesis_explanation='1. From measurements, every module’s cabling is straight‑through: PSU (+) → Control (+) → Load (+) and PSU (−) → Control (−) → Load (−). No connectors are swapped.\n2. However, the PSU and control outputs are measured at about −12 V on the conductors labeled (+) and ~0 V on those labeled (−). So, relative to the intended labelling, the entire system is globally reversed in polarity.\n3. In this design that should cause: (a) the protection diode in the load module to be reverse‑biased, so no current flows to the lamps; (b) the inverted‑cables indicator LED in the control module to be forward‑biased and ON. Those are exactly the observed symptoms: lamp off, red indicator LED on.\n4. The cables themselves and the inter‑module connections have already been verified not faulty; the wall wart/battery provides ~12 V correctly. The only remaining components that can explain the persistent lamp‑off / red‑LED‑on state, with correct straight‑through wiring but globally inverted polarity, are the two polarity‑sensitive elements: the control‑module inverted‑cables indicator LED branch and the series protection diode in the load module.\n5. A fault in either or both of these components (e.g., diode shorted, LED branch miswired or not matching the schematic) would lock the system into a state where reverse polarity is indicated and the lamp never receives proper forward‑biased supply, regardless of how the external cables are connected according to their labels.\n\nTherefore I suspect an internal fault in the control module’s inverted‑cables indicator LED branch and/or the load module’s series protection diode that is preventing correct operation when the system is wired per its labeling, causing the current symptoms.'
