2026-04-16 12:18:31 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply module internal wiring between 12V input jack and PSU Output Cable (+)', 'Power supply module internal wiring between 12V input jack and PSU Output Cable (−)'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show the external wall wart/battery provides a correct +12 V at the input jack, but at the PSU output cables the polarity is reversed: the lead labeled (+) is at about −12 V relative to the lead labeled (−). All downstream modules (control and load) are wired straight‑through, and their components (inverted‑cables LED branch and load protection diode) were confirmed not faulty and are behaving consistently with this reversed polarity. Since the external connections are correct and the cables themselves were already ruled out as faulty, the only consistent root cause is that inside the power supply cube the connections from the 12 V input jack to the two output leads are swapped: the jack’s positive terminal is internally wired to the conductor designated as PSU Output Cable (−), and the jack’s negative terminal is wired to PSU Output Cable (+). This internal miswiring causes the entire chain to see inverted polarity, turning on the inverted‑cables LED and keeping the load lamp off even when the switch is closed. Repairing/reversing these two internal connections in the power supply module will restore correct polarity and normal operation.'
