2026-04-16 12:18:59 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply module green indicator LED orientation / PCB connection'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage measurements show that the 12 V source, the PSU output cables, and the control and load modules are wired consistently: the conductors labelled “+” sit about 12 V below the conductors labelled “−”, but this same inversion appears everywhere in the chain. The red inverted‑cables LED in the control module is lit even though the inter‑module wiring is straight‑through; this is because, from its perspective, the supposed “+12 V” node is actually negative with respect to the supposed 0 V node. \n\nThe latest measurement inside the PSU shows that the green power‑supply LED branch is abnormal: the LED anode sits at −11.99 V while its cathode is at 0 V, so the LED is reverse‑biased by almost the full supply and therefore off. At the same time, both ends of the series resistor are at −11.99 V, i.e., it is effectively shorted out or tied only to the negative node, not in series between the positive and the LED as designed. This is not consistent with a simple external polarity swap; it indicates an internal wiring or PCB error specifically in the indicator branch. \n\nGiven that:\n- The PSU output jack and cables correctly deliver 12 V between the two external nodes.\n- The external modules behave consistently with that polarity.\n- The only element whose behavior contradicts the intended schematic is the green indicator LED/resistor network (reverse‑biased LED, resistor not dropping any voltage).\n\nThe most plausible single fault is that the power supply indicator LED branch has its LED oriented or connected incorrectly on the PCB (e.g., LED reversed and/or resistor tied to wrong node). This miswire both keeps the green LED off and results in the apparent global polarity inversion relative to labels, which in turn makes the control module’s inverted‑cables LED turn on and prevents the load from being driven in the expected orientation. Reworking the green LED and its series resistor to match the schematic nodes (correct anode to positive, cathode to negative, resistor in series with the positive or negative feed) should restore correct reference polarity and normal operation.'
